<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40061a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40061a">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40061a"> 61(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> suspended story / Rawi</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">I cannot take up the Nights, in their present condition, without feeling that the work has been written down from the <i>R&aacute;wi</i> or Nakk&aacute;l, the conteur or professional story-teller, also called Kass&aacute;s and Madd&aacute;h, corresponding with the Hindu Bhat or Bard. To these men my learned friend Baron A. von Kremer would attribute the Mu&apos;allak&aacute;t vulgarly called the <mark><i>Suspended</i> Poems</mark>, as being &ldquo;indited from the relation of the <mark>R&aacute;wi</mark>.&rdquo; <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 163</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Element repeated at <a name="n56126b" href="n56all.htm#n56126b">N56 (VI.B.41):126(b)</a>. In Arabic tradition, treasured poems were written on scrolls or embroidered on sheets of silk that were then &ldquo;suspended,&rdquo; i.e. hung for public display. Cf. <cite>FW</cite> 106.13: <i>The Suspended Sentence</i>. </mm> </dd></dl>
